This file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.

## Commands

All common tasks are defined in `Justfile` and run via `just`:

```sh
just lint          # cargo fmt --check + clippy (-D warnings)
just unit          # cargo test (unit tests only)
just integration   # runs tests from tests/ with --test-threads=5 (requires picodata in PATH)
just test          # unit + integration
just pack          # cargo pike plugin pack → produces target/release/<name>_*.tar.gz
just apply_config  # cargo pike config apply (pushes plugin_config.yaml to running cluster)
```

Run a specific test by name:
```sh
just unit test_name
just integration test_name
```

Local cluster lifecycle (requires `picodata` in PATH):
```sh
cargo pike run [--topology topology.toml]   # start local test cluster
cargo pike stop                              # stop cluster
cargo pike clean                             # purge cluster data
```

## Plugin architecture (Picodata)

### Entry point and registration

Every plugin exposes a `#[service_registrar]` function in `src/lib.rs` that registers one or more services into `ServiceRegistry`. Each service implements the `picodata_plugin::plugin::prelude::Service` trait.

### Service lifecycle

Five callbacks, all must be **idempotent** (may fire multiple times):

| Callback | When |
|---|---|
| `on_start` | Service initializes on a node; register HTTP routes and RPC handlers here |
| `on_stop` | Graceful shutdown; cancel background jobs |
| `on_config_change` | Runtime config updated; receives old and new `Config` values |
| `on_leader_change` | Replicaset leader changed |
| `on_health_check` | Periodic liveness probe |

### Configuration

The `Config` associated type on `Service` maps to a YAML-backed struct. Defaults live in `manifest.yaml`. Runtime values are stored in `_pico_plugin_config` and changed via:
- SQL: `ALTER PLUGIN <name> <ver> SET <service>.<key>='<val>';`
- CLI: `cargo pike config apply` (reads `plugin_config.yaml`)

Use `Config = ()` when the plugin needs no configuration.

### Tiers

Services bind to tiers, not individual nodes (`ALTER PLUGIN ... ADD SERVICE ... TO TIER <tier>`). The plugin `.so` must be present on **all** cluster nodes even if used only on some tiers.

### Migrations

SQL files in `migrations/` annotated with `-- pico.UP` (required) and `-- pico.DOWN` (optional). Executed on `ALTER PLUGIN ... MIGRATE TO <ver>` and rolled back on `DROP PLUGIN ... WITH DATA`.

## SDK API reference

Full rustdoc: https://docs.rs/picodata-plugin/latest/picodata_plugin/

### `internal::instance_info() -> Result<InstanceInfo>`

Current instance metadata — getters: `raft_id()`, `advertise_address()`, `name()`, `uuid()`, `replicaset_name()`, `replicaset_uuid()`, `cluster_name()`, `current_state()`, `target_state()`, `tier()`.

### `internal::raft_info() -> RaftInfo`

RAFT state — `id()`, `term()`, `applied()`, `leader_id()`, `state()` (`RaftState`: Follower / Candidate / Leader / PreCandidate).

### RPC

**Sending:**
```rust
use picodata_plugin::transport::rpc::{self, RequestBuilder, RequestTarget};

let req = rpc::Request::encode_rmp_unnamed(&payload)?;
let resp = RequestBuilder::new(RequestTarget::InstanceName("i1"))
    .plugin_service(PLUGIN_NAME, SERVICE_NAME)
    .plugin_version(env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION"))
    // alternatively: .pico_context(context)
    .path("/my_rpc")
    .input(req)
    .timeout(Duration::from_millis(300))
    .send()?;
let result = rpc::Response::decode_rmp::<MyType>(&resp)?;
```

**`RequestTarget` variants** (`#[non_exhaustive]`):
- `Any` — any instance running the service
- `InstanceName(&str)` — specific instance by name
- `BucketId(u64, bool)` — instance holding bucket; `bool` = master-only
- `TierAndBucketId(&str, u64, bool)` — same, scoped to a tier
- `ReplicasetName(&str, bool)` — instance in named replicaset; `bool` = master-only

**Receiving:**
```rust
use picodata_plugin::transport::rpc::RouteBuilder;

RouteBuilder::from_pico_context(context)
    .path("/my_rpc")
    .register(|req, _ctx| {
        let _payload = rpc::Request::decode_rmp_unnamed::<MyType>(&req)?;
        Ok(rpc::Response::encode_rmp(&result)?)
    })?;
```

### SQL

```rust
picodata_plugin::sql::query("SELECT ... WHERE x = ?")
    .bind(value)
    .fetch::<(String, u64)>()?   // Vec of typed tuples
```

Use `query_raw` for uncached queries. Picodata system tables relevant to plugins:
`_pico_plugin`, `_pico_plugin_config`, `_pico_service`, `_pico_service_route`,
`_pico_instance`, `_pico_peer_address`.

### Metrics

```rust
picodata_plugin::metrics::register_metrics_handler(|| -> String {
    // return Prometheus text-format string
    // called on every GET /metrics on Picodata's built-in HTTP daemon
});
```

### Background jobs

```rust
use picodata_plugin::background::{ServiceWorkerManager, CancellationToken};

// obtain manager from PicoContext in on_start
manager.register_job(|cancel: CancellationToken| {
    while cancel.wait_timeout(Duration::from_secs(1)).is_err() {
        // polling work
    }
})?;

// tag-based cancellation
manager.register_tagged_job(job_fn, &["my-tag"])?;
manager.cancel_tagged(&["my-tag"], Duration::from_secs(5))?;
```

### HTTP server (inbound) — `shors` crate

```rust
use shors::transport::http::{server::Server, route::Builder};

// thread-local server, initialized once
thread_local! {
    static HTTP_SERVER: LazyLock<Server> = LazyLock::new(Server::new);
}

// register in on_start
HTTP_SERVER.with(|srv| {
    let route = Builder::new()
        .with_method("GET")
        .with_path("/v1/my/endpoint")
        .with_middleware(error_middleware)  // optional
        .build(handler_fn);
    srv.register(Box::new(route));
});

// handler signature
fn handler(_ctx: &mut Context, _req: Request) -> anyhow::Result<Response> { ... }
```

### HTTP client (outbound) — `fibreq` crate

Use `fibreq` for all outbound HTTP calls. Standard async runtimes (`reqwest`, `hyper`, tokio) are **incompatible** with Tarantool's fiber scheduler.

### Version pinning

`picodata-plugin` in `Cargo.toml` must **exactly match** the running Picodata version (e.g. `=25.5.2`). Mismatch causes installation failure.

